  "articleSummary": "The article argues that \"Generative UI\" encompasses five distinct implementation patterns with varying technical risks and use cases, and conflating them leads to poor architectural decisions. It categorizes approaches into three core patterns—tool-to-component rendering (safest, fixed UI elements triggered by model decisions), component catalog composition (moderately flexible, structured JSON-driven layouts), and open-ended generation (riskiest, unrestricted UI creation)—emphasizing safety, control, and developer-defined boundaries. Technologies like Vercel AI SDK, Hashbrown, and OpenUI are highlighted as frameworks enabling safer GenUI workflows. The tone is analytical and prescriptive, framing GenUI as a spectrum from \"safe\" to \"expressive\" and urging developers to map their use cases to the appropriate pattern. Key metaphors include a \"map\" for architectural decisions and a \"spectrum diagram\" to visualize risk vs. flexibility tradeoffs.",
